<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUGH LINES; TEENS' HANG-UPS DON'T INCLUDE THE PHONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JERRY ZEZIMA, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES * Jerry Zezima is a columnist for the 
Stamford (Conn.) Advocate. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On March 10, 1876, Alexander Graham Bell made what was, in effect, the first 
telephone call. Everyone knows, of course, that Bell was trying to reach his 
assistant, Thomas Watson. 
</P>
<P>
 What most people don't know is that when Bell spoke into his new invention and 
said, "Mr. Watson, come here, I need you," he heard the voice of Watson's 
teen-age daughter, who replied: "Can I have my dad call you back, Mr. Bell? I'm 
on with my friend Jennifer. Thanks. Bye!" 
</P>
<P>
 Poor Watson never again got another phone call that was for him. Now, more 
than 115 years later, my wife and I find ourselves in the same situation. 
</P>
<P>
 Our two daughters -- Katie, 13, and Lauren, 11 -- spend about 98% of their 
non-school waking hours talking on the telephone. 
</P>
<P>
 I am now convinced that, through a fluke of nature (a subsidiary of AT&T), the 
phone has evolved into a vital organ. 
</P>
<P>
 This has given me a great idea for a new telephone feature: Caller IV, which 
would enable young people to have tiny phones surgically attached to their 
heads so they could receive calls intravenously without having to get up from 
in front of the television. 
</P>
<P>
 Even on those rare occasions (2 a.m., for example) when they are not on the 
phone, it doesn't pay to answer it. That's because it's never for me. 
</P>
<P>
 Occasionally when the phone rings, I have this fantasy that it is Ed McMahon 
or Publishers Clearinghouse or the state lottery or someone representing some 
fantastic giveaway contest that I can win only if I answer the phone now!  
</P>
<P>
 So, every once in a while, in a fit of giddy anticipation, I answer it, only 
to hear a chirpy voice say: "Hi! Is Katie there?" 
</P>
<P>
 Most of the time, even if I am sitting or standing right next to the phone 
when it rings, I won't pick it up -- not just because it's never for me, but 
because my daughters, who ordinarily exhibit all the speed and agility of 
wounded sloths, have been known to answer the phone a mere nanosecond after it 
rings. 
</P>
<P>
 And it does. Incessantly. Sometimes one of my daughters will talk on the phone 
eight times a day with the same person!  
</P>
<P>
 Which raises an interesting question: What the hell do they talk about? 
</P>
<P>
 When I posed this question to my daughters recently, Lauren, whose primary 
phone partner is a very nice girl named Farha, said: "Nothing." 
</P>
<P>
 Katie, who is keeping the telecommunications industry alive with the help of 
her good friends Katalin and Jennifer, was more forthcoming. She said: "Stuff." 
</P>
<P>
 As far as I can tell, there are three main topics of telephone conversation 
among teen-age and preteen girls: 
</P>
<P>
 1. Soap operas. 
</P>
<P>
 2. School. 
</P>
<P>
 3. Troy Aikman. 
</P>
<P>
 And from the snippets of conversation I have been able to pick up, especially 
on those impressive occasions when one of my daughters has been talking on the 
phone and watching TV at the same time, I have concluded that: 
</P>
<P>
 1. Jagger is dying on "General Hospital." 
</P>
<P>
 2. All teachers are nerds. 
</P>
<P>
 3. It's a good thing for Aikman that my daughters and their friends don't have 
his home phone number. 
</P>
<P>
 To be fair, I have been told that teen-age and preteen boys talk on the phone 
just as much as girls do. This is a new one on me, because when I was a boy, 
the lengthiest telephone conversation I had went something like this: 
</P>
<P>
 (My friend Frankie) "Wanna go outside and throw rocks at cars?" 
</P>
<P>
 (Me) "Sure! Bye!" 
</P>
<P>
 Today, I live in fear that teen-agers and preteens will become EMS 
dispatchers, meaning that when I call 911 to report that I am, God forbid, 
having a heart attack, I will invariably hear a chirpy voice on the other end 
say: "I'm on with my friend Katie. Can you call back?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
