<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 KILLED, 3 HURT AS COPTER CRASHES ON POMONA FREEWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NIESON HIMMEL and SHAWN HUBLER, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A private helicopter plummeted onto the Pomona Freeway and burst into flames 
on Tuesday night, killing the occupants of the chopper and injuring at least 
three motorists, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 The crash, which occurred about 9:50 p.m. just west of the Azusa Avenue exit 
in Hacienda Heights, lit up the westbound side of the freeway and tied up 
traffic for five miles in both directions. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was a Robinson F-22 helicopter that apparently hit some power lines and 
then hit a car on the freeway, demolishing it, and then struck another car," 
said Tommy Aina, regional duty officer for the Federal Aviation Administration 
in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Aina said the plane was registered to an aviation service firm based at Chino 
Airport. 
</P>
<P>
 The names of the dead and injured were not immediately available. Nor could 
law enforcement sources confirm the ownership of the aircraft, which sources 
said is owned by Skyline Aviation. 
</P>
<P>
 Scott Tingley, president of Skyline, said the firm owns a Robinson F-22 that 
was flying Tuesday night but would not say whether it was Skyline's chopper 
that had crashed. 
</P>
<P>
 Witnesses said the aircraft had been flying unusually low and apparently 
became entangled in transformer wires. The crash plunged the Pomona Freeway 
into pandemonium as lashing power lines sparked wildly and panicked motorists 
slammed on their brakes, witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
 Coincidentally, they said, the copter crashed just a few car-lengths from a 
California Highway Patrol car in the area. The CHP officer took control of the 
scene within minutes of the explosion. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was like daylight," said Margarita Estrada, 26, a candy store clerk who 
was driving home from work when the crash occurred. 
</P>
<P>
 "All you could see was something coming down out of the sky, hitting the 
freeway and then everything lit up," Estrada said. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was just one big explosion -- pieces of helicopter were lying everywhere, 
and everything smelled like burnt rubber," she added. 
</P>
<P>
 Estrada said that as she gingerly pulled her pickup truck to the shoulder of 
the road, she saw the wreckage of two cars, one of which appeared totaled. The 
helicopter had all but disintegrated, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051194-0015 </DOCNO>
