<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: SUN VALLEY; MIDDLE SCHOOL OKS OPTIONAL UNIFORM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN BYRNES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In an effort to curb student affinity for high-priced fashion trends and 
foster school spirit, Richard E. Byrd Middle School in Sun Valley has joined 
the growing ranks of public schools to adopt an optional uniform. 
</P>
<P>
 "We think we can minimize the cost of wardrobing youngsters and stress school 
spirit and self-esteem at the same time," Byrd Principal Jerry Horowitz said. 
</P>
<P>
 The blue-and-white uniform, with pants and a shirt for boys and pants or a 
plaid skirt and blouse for girls, will cost under $40, Horowitz said. 
</P>
<P>
 The school's leadership council approved the decision after administrators 
received a positive response from parents to a questionnaire about uniforms. 
Administrators expect that about one-third of the students will be wearing the 
uniforms when the program officially begins July 5. 
</P>
<P>
 Several elementary schools in the San Fernando Valley have adopted school 
uniforms, including O'Melveny Elementary in San Fernando, where about 60% of 
the students wear uniforms and San Fernando Elementary School where nearly 80% 
come to school in uniform. SUSAN BYRNES 
</P>
